oolUseID\":\"toolu_01QFBURB8Ni6UJJToey4ZMrb\",\"toolUseID\":\"toolu_01QFBURB8Ni6UJJToey4ZMrb\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-06T12:02:16.172Z\",\"uuid\":\"4a17dece-c0c0-4cf9-9d39-cdd865fd592d\"}\n{\"parentUuid\":\"dfdc8201-d871-483e-84e8-0db69d2520c6\",\"isSidechain\":false,\"userType\":\"external\",\"cwd\":\"/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli\",\"sessionId\":\"57ad503f-9eba-494b-bba0-e3b4e73f710e\",\"version\":\"2.1.70\",\"gitBranch\":\"soph/carry-forward-improvements\",\"slug\":\"modular-tickling-trinket\",\"type\":\"user\",\"message\":{\"role\":\"user\",\"content\":[{\"tool_use_id\":\"toolu_01QFBURB8Ni6UJJToey4ZMrb\",\"type\":\"tool_result\",\"content\":\"     1→# Carry-Forward Improvements\\n     2→\\n     3→## Status: Design\\n     4→\\n     5→## Problem Statement\\n     6→\\n     7→When an agent modifies files during a session, users may commit those changes across\\n     8→multiple `git commit` invocations (split commits). The system needs to track which\\n     9→parts of the agent's work have been committed and which remain, so that:\\n    10→\\n    11→1. Each commit gets its own checkpoint with accurate metadata\\n    12→2. The system knows when all agent work has been committed (carry-forward complete)\\n    13→3. No git refs (shadow branches) need to linger after the session ends\\n    14→\\n    15→### Current Behavior (File-Level)\\n    16→\\n    17→Today, carry-forward operates at **file granularity**:\\n    18→\\n    19→- Agent modifies files A, B, C\\n    20→- User commits A, B → carry-forward tracks file C\\n    21→- User commits C → carry-forward complete\\n    22→\\n    23→For partial commits (`git add -p`), the system detects \\\"file still has changes\\\" via\\n    24→whole-file blob hash comparison + working tree dirty check, but doesn't know WHICH\\n    25→hunks were committed. The shadow branch must persist for the entire carry-forward\\n    26→period to hold the agent's file blobs for comparison.\\n    27→\\n    28→### Desired Behavior (Hunk-Level)\\n    29→\\n    30→The system should track agent changes at the **hunk/diff level**:\\n    31→\\n    32→- Agent modifies `auth.go` (lines 20-24 and lines 100-120)\\n    33→- User commits lines 20-24 via `git add -p` → system knows lines 100-120 remain\\n    34→- User commits lines 100-120 → carry-forward complete for this file\\n    35→- Accurate per-commit attribution: commit 1 gets credit for lines 20-24, commit 2 for 100-120\\n    36→- Shadow branch deleted after first commit; carry-forward uses lightweight local ref\\n    37→\\n    38→## Design\\n    39→\\n    40→### Algorithm: Three-Way Diff (diff3)\\n    41→\\n    42→The core algorithm uses **three-way diffing** to classify every chunk of a file:\\n    43→\\n    44→Given three versions:\\n    45→- **O** (origin/base) — file state before the agent (`state.AttributionBaseCommit`)\\n    46→- **A** (agent) — what the agent wrote (blob stored in carry-forward ref)\\n    47→- **B** (committed) — what the user committed (in HEAD tree)\\n    48→\\n    49→diff3 classifies each region:\\n    50→\\n    51→| O→A | O→B | Classification | Action |\\n    52→|-----|-----|---------------|--------|\\n    53→| unchanged | unchanged | Untouched | Skip |\\n    54→| **changed** | unchanged | Agent change NOT committed | **Remaining** — keep in carry-forward |\\n    55→| unchanged | **changed** | User's own edit | Skip — not from agent |\\n    56→| **same change** | **same change** | Agent change committed | **Consumed** — remove from carry-forward |\\n    57→| **different changes** | **different changes** | Agent change modified by user | **Consumed** (user took ownership) |\\n    58→\\n    59→This naturally handles:\\n    60→- **Partial staging** (`git add -p`): consumed hunks show as \\\"same change in both\\\"\\n    61→- **User edits between commits**: user-only regions classified correctly\\n    62→- **Reverts**: if user reverts an agent hunk, O→B shows unchanged → \\\"remaining\\\" is cleared\\n    63→- **User modifications of agent work**: both-changed-differently → consumed (user took ownership)\\n    64→\\n    65→#### Why diff3 over alternatives\\n    66→\\n    67→| Approach | Pros | Cons |\\n    68→|----------|------|------|\\n    69→| **diff3 (chosen)** | Exact classification, handles all edge cases, proven algorithm | Needs all 3 versions available |\\n    70→| Patch commutation (git-absorb) | Elegant, well-founded in theory | Only detects overlap, not consumption direction |\\n    71→| Reverse-apply check | Simple concept | Fragile with context changes, requires shelling out |\\n    72→| Hunk line-range overlap | Fast | Breaks with line drift, can't handle user edits |\\n    73→\\n    74→### Storage: `refs/entire/carry_forward`\\n    75→\\n    76→A single custom git ref holds all carry-forward data across all sessions:\\n    77→\\n    78→```\\n    79→refs/entire/carry_forward → commit → tree:\\n    80→  <session-id-1>/\\n    81→    src/auth.go          ← agent's file blob (version A)\\n    82→    src/main.go\\n    83→  <session-id-2>/\\n    84→    lib/utils.py\\n    85→```\\n    86→\\n    87→**Properties:**\\n    88→- **Not pushed**: Custom refs outside `refs/heads/` and `refs/tags/` are not pushed\\n    89→  by default. The pre-push hook that pushes `entire/checkpoints/v1` ignores it.\\n    90→- **Not fetched**: Not included in default clone/fetch refspecs.\\n    91→- **Prevents GC**: Git treats all refs as reachability roots. Blobs referenced by\\n    92→  this tree are protected from garbage collection.\\n    93→- **Invisible**: Not shown by `git branch` or `git tag`.\\n    94→- **Single ref**: One ref for all sessions. Adding/removing sessions mutates the tree.\\n    95→  When the last session completes, the ref is deleted entirely.\\n    96→- **go-git compatible**: `Storer.SetReference()` accepts arbitrary ref names. The\\n    97→  codebase already uses this pattern for shadow branches.\\n    98→\\n    99→#### Why not other storage options\\n   100→\\n   101→| Option | Problem |\\n   102→|--------|---------|\\n   103→| Shadow branch (`refs/heads/entire/...`) | Visible in `git branch`, one ref per session |\\n   104→| `entire/checkpoints/v1` tree | Pushed to remote, creates unnecessary commits |\\n   105→| Session state JSON | Can't hold git blob references (GC-unsafe) |\\n   106→| Filesystem (`.entire/snapshots/`) | No dedup, no GC integration, uses disk space |\\n   107→\\n   108→### Session State Additions\\n   109→\\n   110→The session state file (`.git/entire-sessions/<id>.json`) gets minimal new fields:\\n   111→\\n   112→```json\\n   113→{\\n   114→  \\\"carry_forward_base\\\": \\\"abc123def456...\\\",\\n   115→  \\\"carry_forward_files\\\": [\\\"src/auth.go\\\", \\\"src/main.go\\\"]\\n   116→}\\n   117→```\\n   118→\\n   119→- `carry_forward_base`: The base commit hash (O in the diff3 triple). This is the\\n   120→  commit the agent's changes were relative to. Needed to retrieve version O.\\n   121→- `carry_forward_files`: Which files still have remaining agent hunks. Used for quick\\n   122→  checks without reading the carry-forward ref tree.\\n   123→\\n   124→The actual agent file blobs (version A) live in the carry-forward ref, not in the\\n   125→state file. The state file only has lightweight metadata.\\n   126→\\n   127→### Lifecycle\\n   128→\\n   129→```\\n   130→                    ┌─────────────────────────────────────────────┐\\n   131→                    │              ACTIVE SESSION                  │\\n   132→                    │                                             │\\n   133→                    │  Shadow branch: entire/<hash>-<worktree>    │\\n   134→                    │  Stores: file snapshots + transcript        │\\n   135→                    │  (unchanged from today)                     │\\n   136→                    └──────────────────┬──────────────────────────┘\\n   137→                                       │\\n   138→                              First commit\\n   139→                                       │\\n   140→                    ┌──────────────────▼──────────────────────────┐\\n   141→                    │            CONDENSATION                      │\\n   142→                    │                                             │\\n   143→                    │  1. Condense transcript → checkpoints/v1    │\\n   144→                    │  2. Compute remaining files (as today)      │\\n   145→                    │  3. If remaining files:                     │\\n   146→                    │     a. Write agent blobs to carry-forward   │\\n   147→                    │        ref under <session-id>/              │\\n   148→                    │     b. Set carry_forward_base in state      │\\n   149→                    │  4. Delete shadow branch                    │\\n   150→                    └──────────────────┬──────────────────────────┘\\n   151→                                       │\\n   152→                           ┌───────────┴───────────┐\\n   153→                           │                       │\\n   154→                    No remaining files      Has remaining files\\n   155→                           │                       │\\n   156→                    ┌──────▼──────┐    ┌───────────▼──────────────┐\\n   157→                    │  DONE       │    │    CARRY-FORWARD          │\\n   158→                    │  FullyCond. │    │                           │\\n   159→                    │  = true     │    │  On each subsequent       │\\n   160→                    └─────────────┘    │  commit (PostCommit):     │\\n   161→                                       │                           │\\n   162→                                       │  1. For each file in      │\\n   163→                                       │     carry_forward_files:  │\\n   164→                                       │     a. Get O from base    │\\n   165→                                       │     b. Get A from ref     │\\n   166→                                       │     c. Get B from HEAD    │\\n   167→                                       │     d. Run diff3(O, A, B) │\\n   168→                                       │     e. If no \\\"remaining\\\"  │\\n   169→                                       │        chunks → consumed  │\\n   170→                                       │  2. Update ref tree       │\\n   171→                                       │     (remove consumed)     │\\n   172→                                       │  3. Update state file     │\\n   173→                                       │  4. If all consumed →     │\\n   174→                                       │     delete ref subtree,   │\\n   175→                                       │     FullyCondensed=true   │\\n   176→                                       └──────────────────────────┘\\n   177→```\\n   178→\\n   179→### Detailed Flow: PostCommit with Hunk-Level Carry-Forward\\n   180→\\n   181→For each session in `postCommitProcessSession`:\\n   182→\\n   183→1. **Check carry-forward state**: If `carry_forward_files` is empty, skip (no\\n   184→   carry-forward). Fall through to existing file-level logic for active sessions.\\n   185→\\n   186→2. **Load the three versions** for each carry-forward file:\\n   187→   - **O** (base): `repo.CommitObject(carry_forward_base).Tree().File(path)`\\n   188→   - **A** (agent): read from `refs/entire/carry_forward` tree at `<session-id>/<path>`\\n   189→   - **B** (committed): `HEAD.Tree().File(path)` (the just-committed version)\\n   190→\\n   191→3. **Run diff3** per file:\\n   192→   - Use `epiclabs-io/diff3` or equivalent Go library\\n   193→   - Classify each chunk as consumed, remaining, or user-only\\n   194→\\n   195→4. **Determine file status**:\\n   196→   - If no \\\"remaining\\\" chunks → file is fully consumed\\n   197→   - If \\\"remaining\\\" chunks exist → file stays in carry-forward\\n   198→   - If file was deleted in B → consumed (user removed it, agent work is moot)\\n   199→   - If file not in committed files set → skip (not part of this commit)\\n   200→\\n   201→5. **Update carry-forward ref**:\\n   202→   - Remove consumed files from the `<session-id>/` subtree\\n   203→   - Write a new commit on the ref with the updated tree\\n   204→   - If subtree is empty, remove the session's directory entirely\\n   205→\\n   206→6. **Update session state**:\\n   207→   - Update `carry_forward_files` to only remaining files\\n   208→   - If empty → set `FullyCondensed = true`, clean up ref subtree\\n   209→\\n   210→7. **For checkpoint metadata**: The consumed hunks can be recorded in the checkpoint\\n   211→   on `entire/checkpoints/v1` for per-commit attribution.\\n   212→\\n   213→### Detailed Flow: PrepareCommitMsg with Hunk-Level Carry-Forward\\n   214→\\n   215→For sessions with `carry_forward_files`:\\n   216→\\n   217→1. **Check staged files overlap**: Intersect staged files with `carry_forward_files`\\n   218→2. **For overlapping files, run diff3** with staged content (from git index) as B:\\n   219→   - If any chunks classify as \\\"consumed\\\" → agent work is being committed → add trailer\\n   220→   - If no consumed chunks → staged content is user-only or reverted → skip trailer\\n   221→3. This replaces the current `stagedFilesOverlapWithContent` for carry-forward sessions\\n   222→\\n   223→### Edge Cases\\n   224→\\n   225→#### User rebases between split commits\\n   226→- `carry_forward_base` points to a commit that may no longer be in the branch history\\n   227→- But the commit object still exists in the repo (not GC'd — still reachable via reflog)\\n   228→- diff3 still works: O is read from the old base commit's tree, A from carry-forward ref\\n   229→- If the base commit IS GC'd (unlikely within 90-day reflog window): fall back to\\n   230→  file-level comparison\\n   231→\\n   232→#### User amends the first commit\\n   233→- PostCommit fires again for the amend\\n   234→- diff3 runs with the amended commit as B\\n   235→- If amend included more agent hunks → those are now consumed\\n   236→- carry_forward_base doesn't change (still the original pre-agent base)\\n   237→\\n   238→#### Agent session resumes (ENDED → ACTIVE via new TurnStart)\\n   239→- `ActionClearEndedAt` already clears `FullyCondensed`\\n   240→- New SaveStep creates a new shadow branch (normal active session flow)\\n   241→- On next commit, fresh condensation + carry-forward computation\\n   242→- Any leftover carry-forward ref data from the previous ended session is overwritten\\n   243→\\n   244→#### Binary files\\n   245→- diff3 doesn't work on binary files\\n   246→- Fall back to file-level blob hash comparison (current behavior)\\n   247→- Detection: check if file content contains null bytes or use go-git's `IsBinary()`\\n   248→\\n   249→#### File renamed between commits\\n   250→- If user renames a carry-forward file, the old path won't match\\n   251→- Detection: use go-git's `DiffTreeWithOptions` with `DetectRenames: true`\\n   252→- If rename detected, update the path in carry-forward ref and state\\n   253→\\n   254→## Go Libraries\\n   255→\\n   256→| Library | Purpose | Notes |\\n   257→|---------|---------|-------|\\n   258→| `epiclabs-io/diff3` | Three-way merge/diff | Go port, returns classified chunks |\\n   259→| `github.com/sergi/go-diff` | Low-level Myers diff | Already a go-git dependency |\\n   260→| `github.com/bluekeyes/go-gitdiff` | Parse unified diff output | Structured `TextFragment` (hunk) types |\\n   261→| `go-git/go-git/v5` | Git operations, tree diff | `DiffTree()` → `Patch()` → `Chunks()` |\\n   262→\\n   263→## Performance Budget\\n   264→\\n   265→| Operation | Expected Time | Notes |\\n   266→|-----------|--------------|-------|\\n   267→| Read 3 file versions from git | 1-3ms | go-git blob reads |\\n   268→| diff3 per file | 2-10ms | Depends on file size |\\n   269→| 5 carry-forward files | 15-65ms total | Parallelizable |\\n   270→| Update carry-forward ref | 5-10ms | Single tree mutation + commit |\\n   271→| **Total PostCommit overhead** | **20-75ms** | Within <200ms budget |\\n   272→\\n   273→Current PostCommit is <100ms. Adding hunk tracking stays within 200ms for typical cases.\\n   274→\\n   275→## Migration Path\\n   276→\\n   277→1. **Phase 1**: Implement `refs/entire/carry_forward` storage alongside existing shadow\\n   278→   branch carry-forward. Both paths active. New path used when carry-forward ref exists,\\n   279→   old path as fallback.\\n   280→\\n   281→2. **Phase 2**: At condensation time, always write to carry-forward ref instead of\\n   282→   creating a new shadow branch. Shadow branch deleted immediately after first commit.\\n   283→\\n   284→3. **Phase 3**: Remove shadow-branch carry-forward code. Add diff3-based hunk\\n   285→   consumption detection. File-level comparison becomes the fallback for binary files\\n   286→   and error cases.\\n   287→\\n   288→## Files to Modify\\n   289→\\n   290→| File | Change |\\n   291→|------|--------|\\n   292→| `strategy/content_overlap.go` | Add `hunksWithRemainingAgentChanges()` using diff3 |\\n   293→| `strategy/manual_commit_hooks.go` | PostCommit: add carry-forward ref read/write; PrepareCommitMsg: diff3-based overlap |\\n   294→| `strategy/manual_commit_hooks.go` | Replace `carryForwardToNewShadowBranch` with `carryForwardToRef` |\\n   295→| `session/state.go` | Add `CarryForwardBase`, `CarryForwardFiles` fields |\\n   296→| `strategy/manual_commit_condensation.go` | At condensation: write agent blobs to carry-forward ref |\\n   297→| `checkpoint/` (new file) | `carry_forward.go`: ref management (read/write/update/cleanup) |\\n   298→| `strategy/cleanup.go` | Add carry-forward ref cleanup to `ListOrphanedItems` |\\n   299→\\n   300→## Open Questions (Option A)\\n   301→\\n   302→1. Should we store the unified diff text alongside the blob in the carry-forward ref\\n   303→   (for debugging/inspection), or just the blob?\\n   304→2. Should carry-forward ref commits have meaningful messages (for `git log refs/entire/carry_forward`)?\\n   305→3. What's the right stale timeout for carry-forward data? (Currently 7 days for session state)\\n   306→4. Should `entire status` show carry-forward hunk counts per file?\\n   307→\\n   308→---\\n   309→\\n   310→# Option B: Session-Bounded Carry-Forward\\n   311→\\n   312→## Overview\\n   313→\\n   314→A simpler alternative to hunk-level tracking. Instead of tracking which hunks were\\n   315→consumed across sessions, **carry-forward only persists until the next session produces\\n   316→changes**. When a new session's first checkpoint captures the working tree, any ENDED\\n   317→sessions with remaining carry-forward are cleaned up and their uncommitted changes\\n   318→are absorbed into the new session's shadow branch.\\n   319→\\n   320→This accepts a tradeoff: uncommitted changes from Session 1 get attributed to\\n   321→Session 2. In exchange, it eliminates the need for diff3, custom refs, and new\\n   322→libraries entirely.\\n   323→\\n   324→## Design\\n   325→\\n   326→### Core Rule\\n   327→\\n   328→> Carry-forward within a session works as today (file-level, shadow branch).\\n   329→> Cross-session carry-forward does not exist. When a new session produces its first\\n   330→> checkpoint, all ENDED sessions with carry-forward on the same worktree are cleaned up.\\n   331→\\n   332→### Why This Works\\n   333→\\n   334→When a new session's `SaveStep` runs with `StepCount == 0`, `WriteTemporary` uses\\n   335→`IsFirstCheckpoint: true`, which calls `collectChangedFiles()` (`git status --porcelain -z`).\\n   336→This captures **everything** dirty in the working tree — including leftover uncommitted\\n   337→changes from old sessions. The new shadow branch naturally absorbs those changes.\\n   338→\\n   339→No diff computation needed. No new storage needed. The existing shadow branch mechanics\\n   340→handle everything.\\n   341→\\n   342→### Lifecycle\\n   343→\\n   344→```\\n   345→Session 1: Agent changes lines 20-50, 100-120 in auth.go\\n   346→     │\\n   347→     ▼\\n   348→User commits lines 20-50 (git add -p)\\n   349→     │  PostCommit: condense, carry-forward with auth.go (100-120 still in working tree)\\n   350→     │  Shadow branch updated: base=new HEAD, auth.go from working tree\\n   351→     │\\n   352→     ▼\\n   353→Session 1 ends (Phase=ENDED, shadow branch persists for carry-forward)\\n   354→     │\\n   355→     │  ┌─── If user commits lines 100-120 before new session ───┐\\n   356→     │  │  PostCommit: condense ENDED session, FullyCondensed=true │\\n   357→     │  │  Shadow branch deleted. Clean end.                       │\\n   358→     │  └──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘\\n   359→     │\\n   360→     ▼\\n   361→Session 2 starts, first turn produces changes\\n   362→     │  SaveStep (StepCount=0, IsFirstCheckpoint=true):\\n   363→     │    1. collectChangedFiles() captures full working tree\\n   364→     │       (includes auth.go with lines 100-120 from Session 1)\\n   365→     │    2. New shadow branch created with ALL current changes\\n   366→     │    3. ENDED sessions with carry-forward on this worktree:\\n   367→     │       → Mark FullyCondensed=true\\n   368→     │       → Delete their shadow branches\\n   369→     │\\n   370→     ▼\\n   371→Lines 100-120 are now part of Session 2's shadow branch.\\n   372→When committed, they are attributed to Session 2.\\n   373→```\\n   374→\\n   375→### Attribution Tradeoff\\n   376→\\n   377→Lines 100-120 were written by Session 1's agent but get attributed to Session 2.\\n   378→\\n   379→This is acceptable because:\\n   380→\\n   381→- **Session 1's checkpoint for commit 1 is correct**: lines 20-50 are properly\\n   382→  attributed to Session 1 with the right transcript and metadata.\\n   383→- **The user made a choice**: they started a new session without committing the rest.\\n   384→  The remaining changes become part of the new working context.\\n   385→- **When the lines ARE committed**: they are attributed to whatever session is active.\\n   386→  This is accurate — the session that \\\"owns\\\" the working tree at commit time gets credit.\\n   387→- **When the lines are NOT committed in Session 2 either**: they carry forward again\\n   388→  within Session 2 (same mechanism), and get cleaned up when Session 3 starts, or when\\n   389→  they're eventually committed, or via the 7-day stale timeout.\\n   390→- **The alternative is worse**: keeping Session 1's shadow branch alive indefinitely\\n   391→  for attribution precision that the user likely doesn't care about.\\n   392→\\n   393→### Implementation\\n   394→\\n   395→The change is small — roughly 20-30 lines of new code.\\n   396→\\n   397→#### Where: `SaveStep` in `manual_commit_git.go`\\n   398→\\n   399→Before creating the first checkpoint (`StepCount == 0`), find and clean up ENDED\\n   400→sessions with carry-forward on the same worktree:\\n   401→\\n   402→```go\\n   403→// In SaveStep, before WriteTemporary for first checkpoint:\\n   404→if state.StepCount == 0 {\\n   405→    s.cleanupEndedSessionsWithCarryForward(ctx, repo, state.SessionID, state.WorktreePath)\\n   406→}\\n   407→```\\n   408→\\n   409→#### New method: `cleanupEndedSessionsWithCarryForward`\\n   410→\\n   411→```go\\n   412→func (s *ManualCommitStrategy) cleanupEndedSessionsWithCarryForward(\\n   413→    ctx context.Context,\\n   414→    repo *git.Repository,\\n   415→    currentSessionID string,\\n   416→    worktreePath string,\\n   417→) {\\n   418→    sessions, err := s.findSessionsForWorktree(ctx, worktreePath)\\n   419→    if err != nil {\\n   420→        return // Best-effort cleanup\\n   421→    }\\n   422→\\n   423→    for _, old := range sessions {\\n   424→        if old.SessionID == currentSessionID {\\n   425→            continue\\n   426→        }\\n   427→        if old.Phase != session.PhaseEnded {\\n   428→            continue\\n   429→        }\\n   430→        if len(old.FilesTouched) == 0 && old.FullyCondensed {\\n   431→            continue // Already fully condensed\\n   432→        }\\n   433→\\n   434→        // Clean up: mark fully condensed and delete shadow branch\\n   435→        old.FullyCondensed = true\\n   436→        old.FilesTouched = nil\\n   437→        _ = s.saveSessionState(ctx, old)\\n   438→\\n   439→        shadowBranch := getShadowBranchNameForCommit(old.BaseCommit, old.WorktreeID)\\n   440→        _ = deleteShadowBranch(ctx, repo, shadowBranch)\\n   441→\\n   442→        logging.Info(logging.WithComponent(ctx, \\\"checkpoint\\\"),\\n   443→            \\\"cleaned up ended session carry-forward (new session taking over)\\\",\\n   444→            slog.String(\\\"old_session_id\\\", old.SessionID),\\n   445→            slog.String(\\\"new_session_id\\\", currentSessionID),\\n   446→        )\\n   447→    }\\n   448→}\\n   449→```\\n   450→\\n   451→#### What stays the same\\n   452→\\n   453→- Shadow branch creation during active sessions: unchanged\\n   454→- `carryForwardToNewShadowBranch`: unchanged (within-session split commits still work)\\n   455→- `filesWithRemainingAgentChanges`: unchanged\\n   456→- `filesOverlapWithContent` / `stagedFilesOverlapWithContent`: unchanged\\n   457→- PostCommit flow: unchanged\\n   458→- Session state machine: unchanged\\n   459→- `entire/checkpoints/v1` format: unchanged\\n   460→\\n   461→### Comparison: Option A vs Option B\\n   462→\\n   463→| Aspect | Option A (Hunk-Level) | Option B (Session-Bounded) |\\n   464→|--------|----------------------|---------------------------|\\n   465→| **Complexity** | New algorithm (diff3), new ref namespace, new library | ~30 lines of cleanup code |\\n   466→| **Cross-session attribution** | Precise (each hunk attributed to originating session) | Approximate (leftover hunks attributed to new session) |\\n   467→| **Within-session split commits** | Hunk-level precision | File-level precision (same as today) |\\n   468→| **Shadow branch lifetime** | Deleted at first commit (carry-forward moves to ref) | Deleted at first commit OR next session start |\\n   469→| **New dependencies** | `epiclabs-io/diff3` | None |\\n   470→| **New git concepts** | `refs/entire/carry_forward` custom ref | None |\\n   471→| **Risk** | Medium (new algorithm, new storage, new lifecycle) | Low (small change to existing cleanup logic) |\\n   472→| **Migration** | Multi-phase rollout | Single change, backward compatible |\\n   473→| **Handles user never commits** | Carry-forward persists in ref (still needs timeout) | Same as today (7-day stale timeout) |\\n   474→\\n   475→### Recommendation\\n   476→\\n   477→**Start with Option B.** It solves the main problem (lingering shadow branches for\\n   478→ENDED sessions) with minimal risk and code change. The attribution tradeoff is\\n   479→acceptable for most users.\\n   480→\\n   481→Option A can be pursued later if precise cross-session hunk attribution becomes a\\n   482→user-visible requirement (e.g., for billing, compliance, or detailed contribution\\n   483→tracking).\\n   484→\"}]},\"uuid\":\"6e152cae-6a62-40d8-b324-b19b8be1e952\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-06T12:02:16.171Z\",\"toolUseResult\":{\"type\":\"text\",\"file\":{\"filePath\":\"/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli/docs/architecture/hunk-level-carry-forward.md\",\"content\":\"# Carry-Forward Improvements\\n\\n## Status: Design\\n\\n## Problem Statement\\n\\nWhen an agent modifies files during a session, users may commit those changes across\\nmultiple `git commit` invocations (split commits). The system needs to track which\\nparts of the agent's work have been committed and which remain, so that:\\n\\n1. Each commit gets its own checkpoint with accurate metadata\\n2. The system knows when all agent work has been committed (carry-forward complete)\\n3. No git refs (shadow branches) need to linger after the session ends\\n\\n### Current Behavior (File-Level)\\n\\nToday, carry-forward operates at **file granularity**:\\n\\n- Agent modifies files A, B, C\\n- User commits A, B → carry-forward tracks file C\\n- User commits C → carry-forward complete\\n\\nFor partial commits (`git add -p`), the system detects \\\"file still has changes\\\" via\\nwhole-file blob hash comparison + working tree dirty check, but doesn't know WHICH\\nhunks were committed. The shadow branch must persist for the entire carry-forward\\nperiod to hold the agent's file blobs for comparison.\\n\\n### Desired Behavior (Hunk-Level)\\n\\nThe system should track agent changes at the **hunk/diff level**:\\n\\n- Agent modifies `auth.go` (lines 20-24 and lines 100-120)\\n- User commits lines 20-24 via `git add -p` → system knows lines 100-120 remain\\n- User commits lines 100-120 → carry-forward complete for this file\\n- Accurate per-commit attribution: commit 1 gets credit for lines 20-24, commit 2 for 100-120\\n- Shadow branch deleted after first commit; carry-forward uses lightweight local ref\\n\\n## Design\\n\\n### Algorithm: Three-Way Diff (diff3)\\n\\nThe core algorithm uses **three-way diffing** to classify every chunk of a file:\\n\\nGiven three versions:\\n- **O** (origin/base) — file state before the agent (`state.AttributionBaseCommit`)\\n- **A** (agent) — what the agent wrote (blob stored in carry-forward ref)\\n- **B** (committed) — what the user committed (in HEAD tree)\\n\\ndiff3 classifies each region:\\n\\n| O→A | O→B | Classification | Action |\\n|-----|-----|---------------|--------|\\n| unchanged | unchanged | Untouched | Skip |\\n| **changed** | unchanged | Agent change NOT committed | **Remaining** — keep in carry-forward |\\n| unchanged | **changed** | User's own edit | Skip — not from agent |\\n| **same change** | **same change** | Agent change committed | **Consumed** — remove from carry-forward |\\n| **different changes** | **different changes** | Agent change modified by user | **Consumed** (user took ownership) |\\n\\nThis naturally handles:\\n- **Partial staging** (`git add -p`): consumed hunks show as \\\"same change in both\\\"\\n- **User edits between commits**: user-only regions classified correctly\\n- **Reverts**: if user reverts an agent hunk, O→B shows unchanged → \\\"remaining\\\" is cleared\\n- **User modifications of agent work**: both-changed-differently → consumed (user took ownership)\\n\\n#### Why diff3 over alternatives\\n\\n| Approach | Pros | Cons |\\n|----------|------|------|\\n| **diff3 (chosen)** | Exact classification, handles all edge cases, proven algorithm | Needs all 3 versions available |\\n| Patch commutation (git-absorb) | Elegant, well-founded in theory | Only detects overlap, not consumption direction |\\n| Reverse-apply check | Simple concept | Fragile with context changes, requires shelling out |\\n| Hunk line-range overlap | Fast | Breaks with line drift, can't handle user edits |\\n\\n### Storage: `refs/entire/carry_forward`\\n\\nA single custom git ref holds all carry-forward data across all sessions:\\n\\n```\\nrefs/entire/carry_forward → commit → tree:\\n  <session-id-1>/\\n    src/auth.go          ← agent's file blob (version A)\\n    src/main.go\\n  <session-id-2>/\\n    lib/utils.py\\n```\\n\\n**Properties:**\\n- **Not pushed**: Custom refs outside `refs/heads/` and `refs/tags/` are not pushed\\n  by default. The pre-push hook that pushes `entire/checkpoints/v1` ignores it.\\n- **Not fetched**: Not included in default clone/fetch refspecs.\\n- **Prevents GC**: Git treats all refs as reachability roots. Blobs referenced by\\n  this tree are protected from garbage collection.\\n- **Invisible**: Not shown by `git branch` or `git tag`.\\n- **Single ref**: One ref for all sessions. Adding/removing sessions mutates the tree.\\n  When the last session completes, the ref is deleted entirely.\\n- **go-git compatible**: `Storer.SetReference()` accepts arbitrary ref names. The\\n  codebase already uses this pattern for shadow branches.\\n\\n#### Why not other storage options\\n\\n| Option | Problem |\\n|--------|---------|\\n| Shadow branch (`refs/heads/entire/...`) | Visible in `git branch`, one ref per session |\\n| `entire/checkpoints/v1` tree | Pushed to remote, creates unnecessary commits |\\n| Session state JSON | Can't hold git blob references (GC-unsafe) |\\n| Filesystem (`.entire/snapshots/`) | No dedup, no GC integration, uses disk space |\\n\\n### Session State Additions\\n\\nThe session state file (`.git/entire-sessions/<id>.json`) gets minimal new fields:\\n\\n```json\\n{\\n  \\\"carry_forward_base\\\": \\\"abc123def456...\\\",\\n  \\\"carry_forward_files\\\": [\\\"src/auth.go\\\", \\\"src/main.go\\\"]\\n}\\n```\\n\\n- `carry_forward_base`: The base commit hash (O in the diff3 triple). This is the\\n  commit the agent's changes were relative to. Needed to retrieve version O.\\n- `carry_forward_files`: Which files still have remaining agent hunks. Used for quick\\n  checks without reading the carry-forward ref tree.\\n\\nThe actual agent file blobs (version A) live in the carry-forward ref, not in the\\nstate file. The state file only has lightweight metadata.\\n\\n### Lifecycle\\n\\n```\\n                    ┌─────────────────────────────────────────────┐\\n                    │              ACTIVE SESSION                  │\\n                    │                                             │\\n                    │  Shadow branch: entire/<hash>-<worktree>    │\\n                    │  Stores: file snapshots + transcript        │\\n                    │  (unchanged from today)                     │\\n                    └──────────────────┬──────────────────────────┘\\n                                       │\\n                              First commit\\n                                       │\\n                    ┌──────────────────▼──────────────────────────┐\\n                    │            CONDENSATION                      │\\n                    │                                             │\\n                    │  1. Condense transcript → checkpoints/v1    │\\n                    │  2. Compute remaining files (as today)      │\\n                    │  3. If remaining files:                     │\\n                    │     a. Write agent blobs to carry-forward   │\\n                    │        ref under <session-id>/              │\\n                    │     b. Set carry_forward_base in state      │\\n                    │  4. Delete shadow branch                    │\\n                    └──────────────────┬──────────────────────────┘\\n                                       │\\n                           ┌───────────┴───────────┐\\n                           │                       │\\n                    No remaining files      Has remaining files\\n                           │                       │\\n                    ┌──────▼──────┐    ┌───────────▼──────────────┐\\n                    │  DONE       │    │    CARRY-FORWARD          │\\n                    │  FullyCond. │    │                           │\\n                    │  = true     │    │  On each subsequent       │\\n                    └─────────────┘    │  commit (PostCommit):     │\\n                                       │                           │\\n                                       │  1. For each file in      │\\n                                       │     carry_forward_files:  │\\n                                       │     a. Get O from base    │\\n                                       │     b. Get A from ref     │\\n                                       │     c. Get B from HEAD    │\\n                                       │     d. Run diff3(O, A, B) │\\n                                       │     e. If no \\\"remaining\\\"  │\\n                                       │        chunks → consumed  │\\n                                       │  2. Update ref tree       │\\n                                       │     (remove consumed)     │\\n                                       │  3. Update state file     │\\n                                       │  4. If all consumed →     │\\n                                       │     delete ref subtree,   │\\n                                       │     FullyCondensed=true   │\\n                                       └──────────────────────────┘\\n```\\n\\n### Detailed Flow: PostCommit with Hunk-Level Carry-Forward\\n\\nFor each session in `postCommitProcessSession`:\\n\\n1. **Check carry-forward state**: If `carry_forward_files` is empty, skip (no\\n   carry-forward). Fall through to existing file-level logic for active sessions.\\n\\n2. **Load the three versions** for each carry-forward file:\\n   - **O** (base): `repo.CommitObject(carry_forward_base).Tree().File(path)`\\n   - **A** (agent): read from `refs/entire/carry_forward` tree at `<session-id>/<path>`\\n   - **B** (committed): `HEAD.Tree().File(path)` (the just-committed version)\\n\\n3. **Run diff3** per file:\\n   - Use `epiclabs-io/diff3` or equivalent Go library\\n   - Classify each chunk as consumed, remaining, or user-only\\n\\n4. **Determine file status**:\\n   - If no \\\"remaining\\\" chunks → file is fully consumed\\n   - If \\\"remaining\\\" chunks exist → file stays in carry-forward\\n   - If file was deleted in B → consumed (user removed it, agent work is moot)\\n   - If file not in committed files set → skip (not part of this commit)\\n\\n5. **Update carry-forward ref**:\\n   - Remove consumed files from the `<session-id>/` subtree\\n   - Write a new commit on the ref with the updated tree\\n   - If subtree is empty, remove the session's directory entirely\\n\\n6. **Update session state**:\\n   - Update `carry_forward_files` to only remaining files\\n   - If empty → set `FullyCondensed = true`, clean up ref subtree\\n\\n7. **For checkpoint metadata**: The consumed hunks can be recorded in the checkpoint\\n   on `entire/checkpoints/v1` for per-commit attribution.\\n\\n### Detailed Flow: PrepareCommitMsg with Hunk-Level Carry-Forward\\n\\nFor sessions with `carry_forward_files`:\\n\\n1. **Check staged files overlap**: Intersect staged files with `carry_forward_files`\\n2. **For overlapping files, run diff3** with staged content (from git index) as B:\\n   - If any chunks classify as \\\"consumed\\\" → agent work is being committed → add trailer\\n   - If no consumed chunks → staged content is user-only or reverted → skip trailer\\n3. This replaces the current `stagedFilesOverlapWithContent` for carry-forward sessions\\n\\n### Edge Cases\\n\\n#### User rebases between split commits\\n- `carry_forward_base` points to a commit that may no longer be in the branch history\\n- But the commit object still exists in the repo (not GC'd — still reachable via reflog)\\n- diff3 still works: O is read from the old base commit's tree, A from carry-forward ref\\n- If the base commit IS GC'd (unlikely within 90-day reflog window): fall back to\\n  file-level comparison\\n\\n#### User amends the first commit\\n- PostCommit fires again for the amend\\n- diff3 runs with the amended commit as B\\n- If amend included more agent hunks → those are now consumed\\n- carry_forward_base doesn't change (still the original pre-agent base)\\n\\n#### Agent session resumes (ENDED → ACTIVE via new TurnStart)\\n- `ActionClearEndedAt` already clears `FullyCondensed`\\n- New SaveStep creates a new shadow branch (normal active session flow)\\n- On next commit, fresh condensation + carry-forward computation\\n- Any leftover carry-forward ref data from the previous ended session is overwritten\\n\\n#### Binary files\\n- diff3 doesn't work on binary files\\n- Fall back to file-level blob hash comparison (current behavior)\\n- Detection: check if file content contains null bytes or use go-git's `IsBinary()`\\n\\n#### File renamed between commits\\n- If user renames a carry-forward file, the old path won't match\\n- Detection: use go-git's `DiffTreeWithOptions` with `DetectRenames: true`\\n- If rename detected, update the path in carry-forward ref and state\\n\\n## Go Libraries\\n\\n| Library | Purpose | Notes |\\n|---------|---------|-------|\\n| `epiclabs-io/diff3` | Three-way merge/diff | Go port, returns classified chunks |\\n| `github.com/sergi/go-diff` | Low-level Myers diff | Already a go-git dependency |\\n| `github.com/bluekeyes/go-gitdiff` | Parse unified diff output | Structured `TextFragment` (hunk) types |\\n| `go-git/go-git/v5` | Git operations, tree diff | `DiffTree()` → `Patch()` → `Chunks()` |\\n\\n## Performance Budget\\n\\n| Operation | Expected Time | Notes |\\n|-----------|--------------|-------|\\n| Read 3 file versions from git | 1-3ms | go-git blob reads |\\n| diff3 per file | 2-10ms | Depends on file size |\\n| 5 carry-forward files | 15-65ms total | Parallelizable |\\n| Update carry-forward ref | 5-10ms | Single tree mutation + commit |\\n| **Total PostCommit overhead** | **20-75ms** | Within <200ms budget |\\n\\nCurrent PostCommit is <100ms. Adding hunk tracking stays within 200ms for typical cases.\\n\\n## Migration Path\\n\\n1. **Phase 1**: Implement `refs/entire/carry_forward` storage alongside existing shadow\\n   branch carry-forward. Both paths active. New path used when carry-forward ref exists,\\n   old path as fallback.\\n\\n2. **Phase 2**: At condensation time, always write to carry-forward ref instead of\\n   creating a new shadow branch. Shadow branch deleted immediately after first commit.\\n\\n3. **Phase 3**: Remove shadow-branch carry-forward code. Add diff3-based hunk\\n   consumption detection. File-level comparison becomes the fallback for binary files\\n   and error cases.\\n\\n## Files to Modify\\n\\n| File | Change |\\n|------|--------|\\n| `strategy/content_overlap.go` | Add `hunksWithRemainingAgentChanges()` using diff3 |\\n| `strategy/manual_commit_hooks.go` | PostCommit: add carry-forward ref read/write; PrepareCommitMsg: diff3-based overlap |\\n| `strategy/manual_commit_hooks.go` | Replace `carryForwardToNewShadowBranch` with `carryForwardToRef` |\\n| `session/state.go` | Add `CarryForwardBase`, `CarryForwardFiles` fields |\\n| `strategy/manual_commit_condensation.go` | At condensation: write agent blobs to carry-forward ref |\\n| `checkpoint/` (new file) | `carry_forward.go`: ref management (read/write/update/cleanup) |\\n| `strategy/cleanup.go` | Add carry-forward ref cleanup to `ListOrphanedItems` |\\n\\n## Open Questions (Option A)\\n\\n1. Should we store the unified diff text alongside the blob in the carry-forward ref\\n   (for debugging/inspection), or just the blob?\\n2. Should carry-forward ref commits have meaningful messages (for `git log refs/entire/carry_forward`)?\\n3. What's the right stale timeout for carry-forward data? (Currently 7 days for session state)\\n4. Should `entire status` show carry-forward hunk counts per file?\\n\\n---\\n\\n# Option B: Session-Bounded Carry-Forward\\n\\n## Overview\\n\\nA simpler alternative to hunk-level tracking. Instead of tracking which hunks were\\nconsumed across sessions, **carry-forward only persists until the next session produces\\nchanges**. When a new session's first checkpoint captures the working tree, any ENDED\\nsessions with remaining carry-forward are cleaned up and their uncommitted changes\\nare absorbed into the new session's shadow branch.\\n\\nThis accepts a tradeoff: uncommitted changes from Session 1 get attributed to\\nSession 2. In exchange, it eliminates the need for diff3, custom refs, and new\\nlibraries entirely.\\n\\n## Design\\n\\n### Core Rule\\n\\n> Carry-forward within a session works as today (file-level, shadow branch).\\n> Cross-session carry-forward does not exist. When a new session produces its first\\n> checkpoint, all ENDED sessions with carry-forward on the same worktree are cleaned up.\\n\\n### Why This Works\\n\\nWhen a new session's `SaveStep` runs with `StepCount == 0`, `WriteTemporary` uses\\n`IsFirstCheckpoint: true`, which calls `collectChangedFiles()` (`git status --porcelain -z`).\\nThis captures **everything** dirty in the working tree — including leftover uncommitted\\nchanges from old sessions. The new shadow branch naturally absorbs those changes.\\n\\nNo diff computation needed. No new storage needed. The existing shadow branch mechanics\\nhandle everything.\\n\\n### Lifecycle\\n\\n```\\nSession 1: Agent changes lines 20-50, 100-120 in auth.go\\n     │\\n     ▼\\nUser commits lines 20-50 (git add -p)\\n     │  PostCommit: condense, carry-forward with auth.go (100-120 still in working tree)\\n     │  Shadow branch updated: base=new HEAD, auth.go from working tree\\n     │\\n     ▼\\nSession 1 ends (Phase=ENDED, shadow branch persists for carry-forward)\\n     │\\n     │  ┌─── If user commits lines 100-120 before new session ───┐\\n     │  │  PostCommit: condense ENDED session, FullyCondensed=true │\\n     │  │  Shadow branch deleted. Clean end.                       │\\n     │  └──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘\\n     │\\n     ▼\\nSession 2 starts, first turn produces changes\\n     │  SaveStep (StepCount=0, IsFirstCheckpoint=true):\\n     │    1. collectChangedFiles() captures full working tree\\n     │       (includes auth.go with lines 100-120 from Session 1)\\n     │    2. New shadow branch created with ALL current changes\\n     │    3. ENDED sessions with carry-forward on this worktree:\\n     │       → Mark FullyCondensed=true\\n     │       → Delete their shadow branches\\n     │\\n     ▼\\nLines 100-120 are now part of Session 2's shadow branch.\\nWhen committed, they are attributed to Session 2.\\n```\\n\\n### Attribution Tradeoff\\n\\nLines 100-120 were written by Session 1's agent but get attributed to Session 2.\\n\\nThis is acceptable because:\\n\\n- **Session 1's checkpoint for commit 1 is correct**: lines 20-50 are properly\\n  attributed to Session 1 with the right transcript and metadata.\\n- **The user made a choice**: they started a new session without committing the rest.\\n  The remaining changes become part of the new working context.\\n- **When the lines ARE committed**: they are attributed to whatever session is active.\\n  This is accurate — the session that \\\"owns\\\" the working tree at commit time gets credit.\\n- **When the lines are NOT committed in Session 2 either**: they carry forward again\\n  within Session 2 (same mechanism), and get cleaned up when Session 3 starts, or when\\n  they're eventually committed, or via the 7-day stale timeout.\\n- **The alternative is worse**: keeping Session 1's shadow branch alive indefinitely\\n  for attribution precision that the user likely doesn't care about.\\n\\n### Implementation\\n\\nThe change is small — roughly 20-30 lines of new code.\\n\\n#### Where: `SaveStep` in `manual_commit_git.go`\\n\\nBefore creating the first checkpoint (`StepCount == 0`), find and clean up ENDED\\nsessions with carry-forward on the same worktree:\\n\\n```go\\n// In SaveStep, before WriteTemporary for first checkpoint:\\nif state.StepCount == 0 {\\n    s.cleanupEndedSessionsWithCarryForward(ctx, repo, state.SessionID, state.WorktreePath)\\n}\\n```\\n\\n#### New method: `cleanupEndedSessionsWithCarryForward`\\n\\n```go\\nfunc (s *ManualCommitStrategy) cleanupEndedSessionsWithCarryForward(\\n    ctx context.Context,\\n    repo *git.Repository,\\n    currentSessionID string,\\n    worktreePath string,\\n) {\\n    sessions, err := s.findSessionsForWorktree(ctx, worktreePath)\\n    if err != nil {\\n        return // Best-effort cleanup\\n    }\\n\\n    for _, old := range sessions {\\n        if old.SessionID == currentSessionID {\\n            continue\\n        }\\n        if old.Phase != session.PhaseEnded {\\n            continue\\n        }\\n        if len(old.FilesTouched) == 0 && old.FullyCondensed {\\n            continue // Already fully condensed\\n        }\\n\\n        // Clean up: mark fully condensed and delete shadow branch\\n        old.FullyCondensed = true\\n        old.FilesTouched = nil\\n        _ = s.saveSessionState(ctx, old)\\n\\n        shadowBranch := getShadowBranchNameForCommit(old.BaseCommit, old.WorktreeID)\\n        _ = deleteShadowBranch(ctx, repo, shadowBranch)\\n\\n        logging.Info(logging.WithComponent(ctx, \\\"checkpoint\\\"),\\n            \\\"cleaned up ended session carry-forward (new session taking over)\\\",\\n            slog.String(\\\"old_session_id\\\", old.SessionID),\\n            slog.String(\\\"new_session_id\\\", currentSessionID),\\n        )\\n    }\\n}\\n```\\n\\n#### What stays the same\\n\\n- Shadow branch creation during active sessions: unchanged\\n- `carryForwardToNewShadowBranch`: unchanged (within-session split commits still work)\\n- `filesWithRemainingAgentChanges`: unchanged\\n- `filesOverlapWithContent` / `stagedFilesOverlapWithContent`: unchanged\\n- PostCommit flow: unchanged\\n- Session state machine: unchanged\\n- `entire/checkpoints/v1` format: unchanged\\n\\n### Comparison: Option A vs Option B\\n\\n| Aspect | Option A (Hunk-Level) | Option B (Session-Bounded) |\\n|--------|----------------------|---------------------------|\\n| **Complexity** | New algorithm (diff3), new ref namespace, new library | ~30 lines of cleanup code |\\n| **Cross-session attribution** | Precise (each hunk attributed to originating session) | Approximate (leftover hunks attributed to new session) |\\n| **Within-session split commits** | Hunk-level precision | File-level precision (same as today) |\\n| **Shadow branch lifetime** | Deleted at first commit (carry-forward moves to ref) | Deleted at first commit OR next session start |\\n| **New dependencies** | `epiclabs-io/diff3` | None |\\n| **New git concepts** | `refs/entire/carry_forward` custom ref | None |\\n| **Risk** | Medium (new algorithm, new storage, new lifecycle) | Low (small change to existing cleanup logic) |\\n| **Migration** | Multi-phase rollout | Single change, backward compatible |\\n| **Handles user never commits** | Carry-forward persists in ref (still needs timeout) | Same as today (7-day stale timeout) |\\n\\n### Recommendation\\n\\n**Start with Option B.** It solves the main problem (lingering shadow branches for\\nENDED sessions) with minimal risk and code change. The attribution tradeoff is\\nacceptable for most users.\\n\\nOption A can be pursued later if precise cross-session hunk attribution becomes a\\nuser-visible requirement (e.g., for billing, compliance, or detailed contribution\\ntracking).\\n\",\"numLines\":484,\"startLine\":1,\"totalLines\":484}},\"sourceToolAssistantUUID\":\"dfdc8201-d871-483e-84e8-0db69d2520c6\"}\n{\"parentUuid\":\"6e152cae-6a62-40d8-b324-b19b8be1e952\",\"isSidechain\":false,\"userType\":\"external\",\"cwd\":\"/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli\",\"sessionId\":\"57ad503f-9eba-494b-bba0-e3b4e73f710e\",\"version\":\"2.1.70\",\"gitBranch\":\"soph/carry-forward-improvements\",\"slug\":\"modular-tickling-trinket\",\"message\":{\"model\":\"claude-opus-4-6\",\"id\":\"msg_01EivAfumaC3ZUXJ3aM1SXhV\",\"type\":\"message\",\"role\":\"assistant\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"thinking\",\"thinking\":\"Now I understand the full context. The doc describes two options for carry-forward: Option A (hunk-level diff3) and Option B (session-bounded, simpler). The user is now asking about a third signal: detecting when a session should be considered ended based on the state of the working tree and stash.\\n\\nSpecifically, the user is interested in the state where:\\n- Not all files were committed (there are still agent-touched files that weren't committed)\\n- But there are no unstaged changes in the working tree\\n- And the stash is empty\\n\\nThis means the user did something like `git checkout -- <files>` or `git restore <files>` to discard the remaining agent changes, or perhaps they staged everything but didn't commit? No wait - if there are no unstaged changes and the stash is empty, and not everything was committed... that means the agent-touched files that weren't committed were either:\\n\\n\\n- Discarded explicitly by the user, or reset and then discarded\\n\\nSo the se